[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m/*\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mThe helper a(...) creates an empty array of specified dimensions.\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mIt's almost similar to .array~new(...), except for a() which returns an array with 0 dimension (a scalar).\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34mOnce the number of dimension(s) is fixed, it's no longer possible to change it.\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mThis is different from .array~new which returns an array without dimension.\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34mThe number of dimension(s) will be determined by the first access to the array:\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34ma = .array~new; say a[]        -- Not enough positional arguments for method; 1 expected\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34ma = .array~new; say a[1]       -- 1 dimension\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34ma = .array~new; say a[1,1]     -- 2 dimensions\r\n\u001b[0m"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[1;34m*/\r\n"]
[0.000, "o", "\u001b[0m"]
[19.505, "o", "\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[1;34m-- array with 0 dimension (scalar)\r\n\u001b[0m"]
